    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so like, who is actually in charge of it? is it just the lawyer holding onto the cash until everything is signed? it feels a bit weird just leaving a huge amount of money with someone else in the middle of the deal.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You've hit on a very valid point; it does feel a bit like leaving a big pile of cash with someone else, which is exactly why the escrow agent needs to be trustworthy, like a seasoned, reputable lawyer. In Toronto, the lawyer is typically the one managing the escrow, acting as the fiduciary agent. They are legally bound to hold those funds—the down payment, the remaining purchase price, and sometimes funds for closing costs—until every single condition of the agreement is satisfied. They are the gatekeeper, ensuring the keys don't change hands until the money is accounted for and the title is clear.",
      "source": "target",
