    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i guess so. so if something goes wrong, like if the seller doesn't actually have a clear title or the inspection fails, how does the lawyer decide when to give the money back to me vs when to give it to the seller? is there a specific list of things they check?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When things go sideways, like if the seller's title is murky or the inspection reveals a structural issue that's a big deal, the lawyer doesn't just *decide* arbitrarily; they follow a very strict checklist, which is basically the contract itself, plus all the legal requirements. If the inspection fails, for instance, the contract usually dictates what happens next—maybe you get a credit, or you can walk away. If the title is flawed, the lawyer will halt the release of funds until the seller resolves the title issue, often requiring them to provide documentation proving the title is clean.\n\nThink of it like a very complex, multi-stage negotiation where the lawyer is the referee, and the contract is the rulebook. If the seller is found to be in breach of the agreement—say, they hide a massive, dangerous leak that the inspection should have caught—the lawyer will use the escrow funds to protect *you*, the buyer. They won't release the money to the seller until all the \"go\" signals have been given.",
      "source": "target",
